knowledge_graph.title: Common Persimmon
knowledge_graph.description: Diospyros virginiana is a persimmon species commonly called the American persimmon, common persimmon, eastern persimmon, simmon, possumwood, possum apples, or sugar plum. It ranges from southern Connecticut to Florida, and west to Texas, Louisiana, Oklahoma, Kansas, and Iowa.

related_questions.question: Is common persimmon fruit edible?
related_questions.snippet: The thick leaves are glossy and dark green. Fruit valued by wildlife is also edible for humans, but if you decide to go out foraging make sure it's ripe! Persimmons if eaten before prime ripeness are extremely bitter – sometimes a frost is needed to really force fruits into ripening.

related_questions.question: What is common persimmon used for?
related_questions.snippet: The persimmon fruit, which usually ripens in fall, is often used in jams and baked goods. The fruit pulp can be turned into molasses, and the seeds can be turned into a peanut-like oil or roasted and used as a coffee substitute. Dried leaves make a great tea high in vitamin C.

related_questions.question: How big does a common persimmon tree get?
related_questions.snippet: American persimmon is a woody, deciduous tree in the Ebenaceae (ebony) family. It is native to the central and eastern United States and can reach 30 to 80 feet high and 20 to 35 feet wide.
related_questions.title: 30 to 80 feet high

related_questions.question: Why are persimmons so rare?
related_questions.snippet: The common persimmon is rarely grown as a food or ornamental plant. One reason for is that it is extremely slow growing. It takes four to eight years for a tree to bloom for the first time. Then the tree often won't begin producing fruit for another three years.
